                                Report abuseTranscript of Robert BordenRobert BordenFONTSMarriage[2] On September 25th, 1889, Robert Borden married the lovely Laura Bond.  They ended up having no children and bought a house on the south side of Quinpool Road. War [3] Robert Borden was a war leader in the period he was prime minister. He lead Canada through the war despite the problems and work he had back at home. Thesis Statement & Three Premises"Robert Borden had a positive effect on Canada during WW1"Early Career[1] From 1868-1874 Robert taught in his hometown, Grand Pre as well as Matawan, New Jersey. Robert did not see a future in teaching so he went back to Nova Scotia and went to a law firm in Halifax for four years. In 1882, he was asked by Wallace Graham to actually move to Halifax and be apart of the Conservative law firm. He then became the senior partner in October when he was 35 years old.  Who was Robert Borden?Robert Borden was a lawyer born in Grand Pre, Nova Scotia. He became the eight prime minister of Canada from October 10th, 1911 till July 10th, 1920. He then became the chancellor (explain?) of Queen's University. Proved Canada’s independance from WW1Created the Canadian Northern Railway (CNR) when it went bankrupt following WW1 Helped create the law that women had all rights to vote during WW1Proved Canada's independence from WW1Britain made a lot of Canadas decisions and Borden changed thatLet Canada sign the treaty of Versailles for itself instead of the involvement with Britain To have its own seat in the League of NationsVimy Ridge victory lead to independence Created the Canadian Northern Railway (CNR)[4] Borden thought there should be a trasnportation route between prairie regionsSir Thomas White joined Bordens government and put 16 million dollars towards the CNR Thats when the bankruptcy startedThe Bankruptcy [5] When White joined governmnt, he was put in the CNoR positionHe gave 16 million dollars to the CNoR in case of debtsMackenzie and Mann gave 7$ million of their shares towards the government. Government made a deal to Mackenzie and MannHelped create the law that women had all rights to vote during WW1[6] Did not like the idea of women votingHe needed more votes for the 1917 elections so thats when he got the ideaOn Sept 20th, 1917, the parliament said that women (sisters, wives, mothers) of soldiers could voteSuccess!The government liked Bordens idea and in March of 1918, they made the law that all women over ages 21 had the right to vote. Borden succeeded. Robert Borden and the communitySir Robert Borden High School named after him (woohoo)Is currently buried in the Beechwood CemeteryHis statue in Downtown Ottawa"The Prime Ministers of Canada - Robert L. Borden Biography." The Prime Ministers of Canada - Robert L. Borden Biography. Rogers, n.d. Web. 10 Dec. 2013.2. "The Right Honourable Sir Robert Borden." CanadaInfo: Government: Federal: Prime Minister: Former Prime Ministers: Borden. Library and Archives Canada, n.d. Web. 10 Dec. 2013.3. "WarMuseum.ca - History of the First World War - People." WarMuseum.ca - History of the First World War - People. Canadian Museum of Civilization Corporation, n.d. Web. 10 Dec. 2013.4. "Canadian Northern RailwayReporting Mark: CNOR." Canadian Northern Railway. N.p., n.d. Web. 10 Dec. 2013.5. Gagnon, Daivd J. "Canadian National Railways - Part 2 - Rolly Martin Country." Canadian National Railways - Part 2 - Rolly Martin Country. N.p., n.d. Web. 10 Dec. 2013.6. "Extending the Vote." CBCnews. CBC/Radio Canada, 2001. Web. 10 Dec. 2013.Full transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
